<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>8242</anchor> <rss>jms-0032.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-0032</addr>  <route>jms-0032.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>3</month> <day>5</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Exponentiable object</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>E</tex> be an object in a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex> such that all binary cartesian products with <tex>E</tex> exist. We say that <tex>E</tex> is <em>exponentiable</em> when the product endofunctor <tex>- \times  E</tex> on <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex> has a right adjoint, which we shall write <tex>E \Rightarrow-</tex>.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related/> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>8243</anchor> <rss>jms-0031.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-0031</addr>  <route>jms-0031.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>3</month> <day>5</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Exponentiable arrow</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <link href="jms-0033.xml" type="local" title="Carrable map">carrable map</link> <tex>{ E } \xrightarrow{p} { B }</tex> in a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex> is said to be <em>exponentiable</em> when it is <link href="jms-0032.xml" type="local" title="Exponentiable object">exponentiable</link> when viewed as an object of the slice category <tex>{ \mathcal{C} } _{ / B }</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>